Extract the date from time and display top three records¶

In [88]:
udemy_data['published_timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(udemy_data['published_timestamp'])
udemy_data['published_date'] = udemy_data['published_timestamp'].dt.date
udemy_data['published_year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(udemy_data['published_date']).year

Correlation between selected¶

In [120]:
udemy_corr = udemy_data[['price', 'num_subscribers', 'num_reviews', 'num_lectures', 'content_duration', 'published_year']].corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
sns.heatmap(udemy_corr, annot = True, linewidths = 1.2, linecolor = 'white')
plt.xticks(rotation = 75)
plt.show()

The content duration and the number of lectures have a strong positive correlation, since more videos will obviously result in total longer durations. The number of reviews and number of subscribers have a strong positive correlation as well. The higher the number of users, the higher the number of reviews
